# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mesh-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] A **mesh network** is a network topology in which the infrastructure nodes (i.e., bridges, switches, and other infrastructure devices) connect directly, dynamically and non-hierarchically to as many other nodes as possible and cooperate with one another to efficiently route data to and from hosts.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] This lack of dependency on one node allows for every node to participate in the relay of information.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] Mesh networks dynamically self-organize and self-configure, which can reduce installation overhead.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] The ability to self-configure enables dynamic distribution of workloads, particularly in the event that a few nodes should fail.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] This, in turn, contributes to fault-tolerance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] Mesh topology may be contrasted with conventional star/tree network topologies in which the bridges/switches are directly linked to only a small subset of other bridges/switches, and the links between these infrastructure neighbours are hierarchical.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] While star-and-tree topologies are very well established, highly standardized and vendor-neutral, vendors of mesh network devices have not yet all agreed on common standards, and interoperability between devices from different vendors is not yet assured.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] Mesh networks can relay messages using either a *flooding* or a *routing* technique, which makes them different from non-mesh networks.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] A routed message is propagated along a path by *hopping* from node to node until it reaches its destination.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] To ensure that all its paths are available, the network must allow for continuous connections and must reconfigure itself around broken paths, using *self-healing* algorithms such as Shortest Path Bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links).
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] Self-healing allows a routing-based network to operate when a node breaks down or when a connection becomes unreliable.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] The network is typically quite reliable, as there is often more than one path between a source and a destination in the network.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] Although mostly used in wireless situations, this concept can also apply to wired networks and to software interaction.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] A mesh network whose nodes are all connected to each other is a fully connected network.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] Fully connected wired networks are more secure and reliable: problems in a cable affect only the two nodes attached to it.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] In such networks, however, the number of cables, and therefore the cost, goes up rapidly as the number of nodes increases.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] Shortest path bridging and TRILL each allow Ethernet switches to be connected in a mesh topology and allow for all paths to be active.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] IP routing supports multiple paths from source to destination.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] A wireless mesh network (WMN) is a network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:mesh-networking/mesh-networking] It can also be a form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A **wireless ad hoc network** (**WANET**) or **mobile ad hoc network** (**MANET**) is a decentralized type of wireless network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The network is ad hoc because it does not rely on a pre-existing infrastructure, such as routers or wireless access points.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Instead, each node participates in routing by forwarding data for other nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The determination of which nodes forward data is made dynamically on the basis of network connectivity and the routing algorithm in use.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Such wireless networks lack the complexities of infrastructure setup and administration, enabling devices to create and join networks "on the fly".
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each device in a MANET is free to move independently in any direction, and will therefore change its links to other devices frequently.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each must forward traffic unrelated to its own use, and therefore be a router.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The primary challenge in building a MANET is equipping each device to continuously maintain the information required to properly route traffic.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Such networks may operate by themselves or may be connected to the larger Internet.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] They may contain one or multiple and different transceivers between nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This results in a highly dynamic, autonomous topology.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] MANETs usually have a routable networking environment on top of a link layer ad hoc network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The earliest wireless data network was called PRNET, the packet radio network, and was sponsored by Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) in the early 1970s.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] (BBN) and SRI International designed, built, and experimented with these earliest systems.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Experimenters included Robert Kahn, Jerry Burchfiel, and Ray Tomlinson.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Similar experiments took place in the amateur radio community with the x25 protocol.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] These early packet radio systems predated the Internet, and indeed were part of the motivation of the original Internet Protocol suite.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Later DARPA experiments included the Survivable Radio Network (SURAN) project, which took place in the 1980s.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A successor to these systems was fielded in the mid-1990s for the US Army, and later other nations, as the Near-term digital radio.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Another third wave of academic and research activity started in the mid-1990s with the advent of inexpensive 802.11 radio cards for personal computers.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Current wireless ad hoc networks are designed primarily for military utility.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Problems with packet radios are: (1) bulky elements, (2) slow data rate, (3) unable to maintain links if mobility is high.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The project did not proceed much further until the early 1990s when wireless ad hoc networks were born.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The growth of laptops and 802.11/Wi-Fi wireless networking have made MANETs a popular research topic since the mid-1990s.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Many academic papers evaluate protocols and their abilities, assuming varying degrees of mobility within a bounded space, usually with all nodes within a few hops of each other.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Different protocols are then evaluated based on measures such as the packet drop rate, the overhead introduced by the routing protocol, end-to-end packet delays, network throughput, ability to scale, etc.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In the early 1990s, Charles Perkins from SUN Microsystems USA, and Chai Keong Toh from Cambridge University separately started to work on a different Internet, that of a wireless ad hoc network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Perkins was working on the dynamic addressing issues.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Toh worked on a new routing protocol, which was known as ABR – associativity-based routing.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Perkins eventually proposed DSDV – Destination Sequence Distance Vector routing, which was based on distributed distance vector routing.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Toh's proposal was an on-demand based routing, i.e. routes are discovered on-the-fly in real-time as and when needed.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] ABR was implemented successfully into Linux OS on Lucent WaveLAN 802.11a enabled laptops and a practical ad hoc mobile network was therefore proven to be possible in 1999.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Another routing protocol known as AODV was subsequently introduced and later proven and implemented in 2005.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In 2007, David Johnson and Dave Maltz proposed DSR – Dynamic Source Routing.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Minimal configuration and quick deployment make ad hoc networks suitable for emergency situations like natural disasters or military conflicts.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The presence of dynamic and adaptive routing protocols enables ad hoc networks to be formed quickly.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A mobile ad hoc network (MANET) is a continuously self-configuring, self-organizing, infrastructure-less network of mobile devices connected without wires.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] It is sometimes known as "on-the-fly" networks or "spontaneous networks".
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] VANETs are used for communication between vehicles and roadside equipment.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Intelligent vehicular ad hoc networks (InVANETs) are a kind of artificial intelligence that helps vehicles to behave in intelligent manners during vehicle-to-vehicle collisions, accidents.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Vehicles are using radio waves to communicate with each other, creating communication networks instantly on-the-fly while vehicles move along roads.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] VANET needs to be secured with lightweight protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A SPAN leverages existing hardware (primarily Wi-Fi and Bluetooth) and software (protocols) in commercially available smartphones to create peer-to-peer networks without relying on cellular carrier networks, wireless access points, or traditional network infrastructure.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] SPANs differ from traditional hub and spoke networks, such as Wi-Fi Direct, in that they support multi-hop relays and there is no notion of a group leader so peers can join and leave at will without destroying the network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Apple's iPhone with iOS version 7.0 and higher is capable of multi-peer ad hoc mesh networking.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Mesh networks take their name from the topology of the resultant network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In a fully connected mesh, each node is connected to every other node, forming a "mesh".
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A partial mesh, by contrast, has a topology in which some nodes are not connected to others, although this term is seldom in use.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks can take the form of a mesh networks or others.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A wireless ad hoc network does not have fixed topology, and its connectivity among nodes is totally dependent on the behavior of the devices, their mobility patterns, distance with each other, etc.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Hence, wireless mesh networks are a particular type of wireless ad hoc networks, with special emphasis on the resultant network topology.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] While some wireless mesh networks (particularly those within a home) have relatively infrequent mobility and thus infrequent link breaks, other more mobile mesh networks require frequent routing adjustments to account for lost links.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Military or tactical MANETs are used by military units with emphasis on data rate, real-time requirement, fast re-routing during mobility, data security, radio range, and integration with existing systems.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Common radio waveforms include the US Army's JTRS SRW and Silvus Technologies MN-MIMO Waveform (Mobile Networked MIMO),.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Ad hoc mobile communications come in well to fulfill this need, especially its infrastructureless nature, fast deployment, and operation.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Military MANETs are used by military units with an emphasis on rapid deployment, infrastructureless, all-wireless networks (no fixed radio towers), robustness (link breaks are no problem), security, range, and instant operation.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Flying ad hoc networks (FANETs) are composed of unmanned aerial vehicles, allowing great mobility and providing connectivity to remote areas.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Unmanned aerial vehicle, is an aircraft with no pilot on board.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] UAVs can be remotely controlled (i.e., flown by a pilot at a ground control station) or can fly autonomously based on pre-programmed flight plans.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Civilian usage of UAV include modeling 3D terrains, package delivery (Logistics), etc.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] UAVs have also been used by US Air Force for data collection and situation sensing, without risking the pilot in a foreign unfriendly environment.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With wireless ad hoc network technology embedded into the UAVs, multiple UAVs can communicate with each other and work as a team, collaboratively to complete a task and mission.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] If a UAV is destroyed by an enemy, its data can be quickly offloaded wirelessly to other neighboring UAVs.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The UAV ad hoc communication network is also sometimes referred to UAV instant sky network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] More generally, aerial MANET in UAVs are now (as of 2021) successfully implemented and operational as mini tactical reconnaissance ISR UAVs like the BRAMOR C4EYE from Slovenia.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Navy ships traditionally use satellite communications and other maritime radios to communicate with each other or with ground station back on land.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] However, such communications are restricted by delays and limited bandwidth.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks enable ship-area-networks to be formed while at sea, enabling high-speed wireless communications among ships, enhancing their sharing of imaging and multimedia data, and better co-ordination in battlefield operations.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some defense companies (such as Rockwell Collins, Silvus Technologies and Rohde & Schwartz) have produced products that enhance ship-to-ship and ship-to-shore communications.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Sensors are useful devices that collect information related to a specific parameter, such as noise, temperature, humidity, pressure, etc.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Sensors are increasingly connected via wireless to allow large-scale collection of sensor data.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With a large sample of sensor data, analytics processing can be used to make sense out of these data.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The connectivity of wireless sensor networks rely on the principles behind wireless ad hoc networks, since sensors can now be deploy without any fixed radio towers, and they can now form networks on-the-fly.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] "Smart Dust" was one of the early projects done at U C Berkeley, where tiny radios were used to interconnect smart dust.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] More recently, mobile wireless sensor networks (MWSNs) have also become an area of academic interest.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Efforts have been made to co-ordinate and control a group of robots to undertake collaborative work to complete a task.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Centralized control is often based on a "star" approach, where robots take turns to talk to the controller station.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] However, with wireless ad hoc networks, robots can form a communication network on-the-fly, i.e., robots can now "talk" to each other and collaborate in a distributed fashion.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With a network of robots, the robots can communicate among themselves, share local information, and distributively decide how to resolve a task in the most effective and efficient way.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Another civilian use of wireless ad hoc network is for public safety.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] At times of disasters (floods, storms, earthquakes, fires, etc.), a quick and instant wireless communication network is necessary.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Especially at times of earthquakes when radio towers had collapsed or were destroyed, wireless ad hoc networks can be formed independently.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Firefighters and rescue workers can use ad hoc networks to communicate and rescue those injured.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Commercial radios with such capability are available on the market.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks allow sensors, videos, instruments, and other devices to be deployed and interconnected wirelessly for clinic and hospital patient monitoring, doctor and nurses alert notification, and also making senses of such data quickly at fusion points, so that lives can be saved.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] MANETS can be used for facilitating the collection of sensor data for data mining for a variety of applications such as air pollution monitoring and different types of architectures can be used for such applications.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A key characteristic of such applications is that nearby sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires the techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] By measuring the spatial correlation between data sampled by different sensors, a wide class of specialized algorithms can be developed to develop more efficient spatial data mining algorithms as well as more efficient routing strategies.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Also, researchers have developed performance models for MANET to apply queueing theory.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Several books and works have revealed the technical and research challenges facing wireless ad hoc networks or MANETs.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The obvious appeal of MANETs is that the network is decentralised and nodes/devices are mobile, that is to say there is no fixed infrastructure which provides the possibility for numerous applications in different areas such as environmental monitoring, disaster relief and military communications.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Since the early 2000s, interest in MANETs has greatly increased which, in part, is due to the fact mobility can improve network capacity, shown by Grossglauser and Tse along with the introduction of new technologies.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One main advantage to a decentralised network is that they are typically more robust than centralised networks due to the multi-hop fashion in which information is relayed.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] For example, in the cellular network setting, a drop in coverage occurs if a base station stops working, however the chance of a single point of failure in a MANET is reduced significantly since the data can take multiple paths.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Since the MANET architecture evolves with time it has the potential to resolve issues such as isolation/disconnection from the network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Further advantages of MANETS over networks with a fixed topology include flexibility (an ad hoc network can be created anywhere with mobile devices), scalability (adding nodes to the network is easy) and lower administration costs (no need to build an infrastructure first).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With a time evolving network it is clear we should expect variations in network performance due to no fixed architecture (no fixed connections).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Finally, finding a model that accurately represents human mobility whilst remaining mathematically tractable remains an open problem due to the large range of factors that influence it.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some typical models used include the random walk, random waypoint and levy flight models.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wireless ad hoc networks can operate over different types of radios.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] All radios use modulation to move information over a certain bandwidth of radio frequencies.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given the need to move large amounts of information quickly over long distances, a MANET radio channel ideally has large bandwidth (e.g. amount of radio spectrum), lower frequencies, and higher power.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given the desire to communicate with many other nodes ideally simultaneously, many channels are needed.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given radio spectrum is shared and regulated, there is less bandwidth available at lower frequencies.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Processing many radio channels requires many resources.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Given the need for mobility, small size and lower power consumption are very important.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Picking a MANET radio and modulation has many trade-offs; many start with the specific frequency and bandwidth they are allowed to use.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Wi-Fi ad hoc uses the unlicensed ISM 2.4 GHz radios.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] They can also be used on 5.8 GHz radios.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The higher the frequency, such as those of 300 GHz, absorption of the signal will be more predominant.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Army tactical radios usually employ a variety of UHF and SHF radios, including those of VHF to provide a variety of communication modes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] At the 800, 900, 1200, 1800 MHz range, cellular radios are predominant.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some cellular radios use ad hoc communications to extend cellular range to areas and devices not reachable by the cellular base station.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Next generation Wi-Fi known as 802.11ax provides low delay, high capacity (up to 10 Gbit/s) and low packet loss rate, offering 12 streams – 8 streams at 5 GHz and 4 streams at 2.4 GHz.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] IEEE 802.11ax uses 8x8 MU-MIMO, OFDMA, and 80 MHz channels.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Hence, 802.11ax has the ability to form high capacity Wi-Fi ad hoc networks.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] At 60 GHz, there is another form of Wi-Fi known as WiGi – wireless gigabit.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This has the ability to offer up to 7 Gbit/s throughput.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Currently, WiGi is targeted to work with 5G cellular networks.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Circa 2020, the general consensus finds the 'best' modulation for moving information over higher frequency waves to be orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing, as used in 4G LTE, 5G, and Wi-Fi.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The challenges affecting MANETs span from various layers of the OSI protocol stack.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The media access layer (MAC) has to be improved to resolve collisions and hidden terminal problems.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The network layer routing protocol has to be improved to resolve dynamically changing network topologies and broken routes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The transport layer protocol has to be improved to handle lost or broken connections.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The session layer protocol has to deal with discovery of servers and services.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A major limitation with mobile nodes is that they have high mobility, causing links to be frequently broken and reestablished.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Moreover, the bandwidth of a wireless channel is also limited, and nodes operate on limited battery power, which will eventually be exhausted.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] These factors make the design of a mobile ad hoc network challenging.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The cross-layer design deviates from the traditional network design approach in which each layer of the stack would be made to operate independently.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The modified transmission power will help that node to dynamically vary its propagation range at the physical layer.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This is because the propagation distance is always directly proportional to transmission power.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This information is passed from the physical layer to the network layer so that it can take optimal decisions in routing protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A major advantage of this protocol is that it allows access of information between physical layer and top layers (MAC and network layer).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Some elements of the software stack were developed to allow code updates *in situ*, i.e., with the nodes embedded in their physical environment and without needing to bring the nodes back into the lab facility.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Such software updating relied on epidemic mode of dissemination of information and had to be done both efficiently (few network transmissions) and fast.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Routing in wireless ad hoc networks or MANETs generally falls into three categories, namely: proactive routing, reactive routing, and hybrid routing.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This type of protocols maintains fresh lists of destinations and their routes by periodically distributing routing tables throughout the network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] As in a fix net nodes maintain routing tables.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Distance-vector protocols are based on calculating the direction and distance to any link in a network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] "Direction" usually means the next hop address and the exit interface.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] "Distance" is a measure of the cost to reach a certain node.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The least cost route between any two nodes is the route with minimum distance.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each node maintains a vector (table) of minimum distance to every node.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The cost of reaching a destination is calculated using various route metrics.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] RIP uses the hop count of the destination whereas IGRP takes into account other information such as node delay and available bandwidth.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This type of protocol finds a route based on user and traffic demand by flooding the network with Route Request or Discovery packets.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] However, clustering can be used to limit flooding.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The latency incurred during route discovery is not significant compared to periodic route update exchanges by all nodes in the network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Is a simple routing algorithm in which every incoming packet is sent through every outgoing link except the one it arrived on.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Flooding is used in bridging and in systems such as Usenet and peer-to-peer file sharing and as part of some routing protocols, including OSPF, DVMRP, and those used in wireless ad hoc networks.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This type of protocol combines the advantages of *proactive* and *reactive routing*.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The routing is initially established with some proactively prospected routes and then serves the demand from additionally activated nodes through reactive flooding.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The choice of one or the other method requires predetermination for typical cases.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Reaction to traffic demand depends on gradient of traffic volume.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Position-based routing methods use information on the exact locations of the nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] This information is obtained for example via a GPS receiver.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Based on the exact location the best path between source and destination nodes can be determined.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Links are influenced by the node's resources (e.g., transmitter power, computing power and memory) and behavioral properties (e.g., reliability), as well as link properties (e.g. length-of-link and signal loss, interference and noise).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Since links can be connected or disconnected at any time, a functioning network must be able to cope with this dynamic restructuring, preferably in a way that is timely, efficient, reliable, robust, and scalable.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The network must allow any two nodes to communicate by relaying the information via other nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A "path" is a series of links that connects two nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Various routing methods use one or two paths between any two nodes; flooding methods use all or most of the available paths.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In most wireless ad hoc networks, the nodes compete for access to shared wireless medium, often resulting in collisions (interference).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Collisions can be handled using centralized scheduling or distributed contention access protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Using cooperative wireless communications improves immunity to interference by having the destination node combine self-interference and other-node interference to improve decoding of the desired signals.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One key problem in wireless ad hoc networks is foreseeing the variety of possible situations that can occur.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] As a result, modeling and simulation (M&S) using extensive parameter sweeping and what-if analysis becomes an extremely important paradigm for use in ad hoc networks.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One solution is the use of simulation tools like OPNET, NetSim or ns2.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) developed a Mobile Ad-Hoc Network emulation testbed, where algorithms and applications were subjected to representative wireless network conditions.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The testbed was based on a version of the "MANE" (Mobile Ad hoc Network Emulator) software originally developed by NRL.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The traditional model is the random geometric graph.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Early work included simulating ad hoc mobile networks on sparse and densely connected topologies.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Nodes are firstly scattered in a constrained physical space randomly.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Each node then has a predefined fixed cell size (radio range).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] A node is said to be connected to another node if this neighbor is within its radio range.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Nodes are then moved (migrated away) based on a random model, using random walk or brownian motion.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Different mobility and number of nodes present yield different route length and hence different number of multi-hops.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] These are graphs consisting of a set of nodes placed according to a point process in some usually bounded subset of the n-dimensional plane, mutually coupled according to a Boolean probability mass function of their spatial separation (see e.g. unit disk graphs).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] The connections between nodes may have different weights to model the difference in channel attenuations.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One can then study network observables (such as connectivity, centrality or the degree distribution) from a graph-theoretic perspective.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] One can further study network protocols and algorithms to improve network throughput and fairness.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Most wireless ad hoc networks do not implement any network access control, leaving these networks vulnerable to resource consumption attacks where a malicious node injects packets into the network with the goal of depleting the resources of the nodes relaying the packets.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] To thwart or prevent such attacks, it was necessary to employ authentication mechanisms that ensure that only authorized nodes can inject traffic into the network.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Even with authentication, these networks are vulnerable to packet dropping or delaying attacks, whereby an intermediate node drops the packet or delays it, rather than promptly sending it to the next hop.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] In a multicast and dynamic environment, establishing temporary 1:1 secure 'sessions' using PKI with every other node is not feasible (like is done with HTTPS, most VPNs, etc. at the transport layer).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Instead, a common solution is to use pre-shared keys for symmetric, authenticated encryption at the link layer, for example MACsec using AES-256-GCM.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] With this method, every properly formatted packet received is authenticated then passed along for decryption or dropped.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] It also means the key(s) in each node must be changed more often and simultaneously (e.g. to avoid reusing an IV).
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Trust establishment and management in MANETs face challenges due to resource constraints and the complex interdependency of networks.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Researchers of trust management in MANET suggested that such complex interactions require a composite trust metric that captures aspects of communications and social networks, and corresponding trust measurement, trust distribution, and trust management schemes.
[src:mesh-networking/mobile-ad-hoc-network] Continuous monitoring of every node within a MANET is necessary for trust and reliability but difficult because it by definition is dis-continuous, 2) it requires input from the node itself and 3) from its 'nearby' peers.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Network topology is the topological structure of a network and may be depicted physically or logically.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] It is an application of graph theory wherein communicating devices are modeled as nodes and the connections between the devices are modeled as links or lines between the nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] **Physical topology** is the placement of the various components of a network (e.g., device location and cable installation), while **logical topology** illustrates how data flows within a network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Distances between nodes, physical interconnections, transmission rates, or signal types may differ between two different networks, yet their logical topologies may be identical.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A network's physical topology is a particular concern of the physical layer of the OSI model.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Examples of network topologies are found in local area networks (LAN), a common computer network installation.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Any given node in the LAN has one or more physical links to other devices in the network; graphically mapping these links results in a geometric shape that can be used to describe the physical topology of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A wide variety of physical topologies have been used in LANs, including ring, bus, mesh and star.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Conversely, mapping the data flow between the components determines the logical topology of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In comparison, Controller Area Networks, common in vehicles, are primarily distributed control system networks of one or more controllers interconnected with sensors and actuators over, invariably, a physical bus topology.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Two basic categories of network topologies exist: physical topologies and logical topologies.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The transmission medium layout used to link devices is the physical topology of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] For conductive or fiber optical mediums, this refers to the layout of cabling, the locations of nodes, and the links between the nodes and the cabling.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The physical topology of a network is determined by the capabilities of the network access devices and media, the level of control or fault tolerance desired, and the cost associated with cabling or telecommunication circuits.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In contrast, logical topology is the way that the signals act on the network media, or the way that the data passes through the network from one device to the next without regard to the physical interconnection of the devices.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A network's logical topology is not necessarily the same as its physical topology.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] For example, the original twisted pair Ethernet using repeater hubs was a logical bus topology carried on a physical star topology.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Token Ring is a logical ring topology, but is wired as a physical star from the media access unit.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Logical topologies are often closely associated with media access control methods and protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Some networks are able to dynamically change their logical topology through configuration changes to their routers and switches.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The transmission media (often referred to in the literature as the *physical media*) used to link devices to form a computer network include electrical cables (Ethernet, HomePNA, power line communication, G.hn), optical fiber (fiber-optic communication), and radio waves (wireless networking).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In the OSI model, these are defined at layers 1 and 2 — the physical layer and the data link layer.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A widely adopted *family* of transmission media used in local area network (LAN) technology is collectively known as Ethernet.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The media and protocol standards that enable communication between networked devices over Ethernet are defined by IEEE 802.3.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Ethernet transmits data over both copper and fiber cables.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Wireless LAN standards (e.g., those defined by IEEE 802.11) use radio waves, or others use infrared signals as a transmission medium.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Power line communication uses a building's power cabling to transmit data.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The orders of the following wired technologies are, roughly, from slowest to fastest transmission speed.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Price is a main factor distinguishing wired and wireless technology options in a business.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Wireless options command a price premium that can make purchasing wired computers, printers and other devices a financial benefit.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Before making the decision to purchase hard-wired technology products, a review of the restrictions and limitations of the selections is necessary.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Business and employee needs may override any cost considerations.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Both cases have a large round-trip delay time, which gives slow two-way communication, but does not prevent sending large amounts of information.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Network nodes are the points of connection of the transmission medium to transmitters and receivers of the electrical, optical, or radio signals carried in the medium.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Nodes may be associated with a computer, but certain types may have only a microcontroller at a node or possibly no programmable device at all.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In the simplest of serial arrangements, one RS-232 transmitter can be connected by a pair of wires to one receiver, forming two nodes on one link, or a point-to-point topology.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Some protocols permit a single node to only either transmit or receive (e.g., ARINC 429).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Other protocols have nodes that can both transmit and receive into a single channel (e.g., CAN can have many transceivers connected to a single bus).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A network interface controller (NIC) is computer hardware that provides a computer with the ability to access the transmission media, and has the ability to process low-level network information.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] For example, the NIC may have a connector for accepting a cable, or an aerial for wireless transmission and reception, and the associated circuitry.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The NIC responds to traffic addressed to a network address for either the NIC or the computer as a whole.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In Ethernet networks, each network interface controller has a unique Media Access Control (MAC) address—usually stored in the controller's permanent memory.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] To avoid address conflicts between network devices, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) maintains and administers MAC address uniqueness.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The size of an Ethernet MAC address is six octets.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The three most significant octets are reserved to identify NIC manufacturers.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] These manufacturers, using only their assigned prefixes, uniquely assign the three least-significant octets of every Ethernet interface they produce.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A repeater is an electronic device that receives a network signal, cleans it of unnecessary noise and regenerates it.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The signal may be reformed or retransmitted at a higher power level, to the other side of an obstruction, possibly using a different transmission medium, so that the signal can cover longer distances without degradation.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Commercial repeaters have extended RS-232 segments from 15 meters to over a kilometer.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In most twisted pair Ethernet configurations, repeaters are required for cable that runs longer than 100 meters.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] With fiber optics, repeaters can be tens or even hundreds of kilometers apart.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Repeaters work within the physical layer of the OSI model; that is, there is no end-to-end change in the physical protocol across the repeater, or repeater pair, even if a different physical layer may be used between the ends of the repeater, or repeater pair.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Repeaters require a small amount of time to regenerate the signal.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This can cause a propagation delay that affects network performance and may affect proper function.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] As a result, many network architectures limit the number of repeaters that can be used in a row, e.g., the Ethernet 5-4-3 rule.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A repeater with multiple ports is known as hub, an Ethernet hub in Ethernet networks, a USB hub in USB networks.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A network bridge connects and filters traffic between two network segments at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to form a single network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This breaks the network's collision domain but maintains a unified broadcast domain.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Network segmentation breaks down a large, congested network into an aggregation of smaller, more efficient networks.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A network switch is a device that forwards and filters OSI layer 2 datagrams (frames) between ports based on the destination MAC address in each frame.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A switch is distinct from a hub in that it only forwards the frames to the physical ports involved in the communication, rather than all ports connected.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] It can be thought of as a multi-port bridge.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] It learns to associate physical ports to MAC addresses by examining the source addresses of received frames.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] If an unknown destination is targeted, the switch broadcasts to all ports but the source.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Switches normally have numerous ports, facilitating a star topology for devices and cascading additional switches.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Multi-layer switches are capable of routing based on layer 3 addressing or additional logical levels.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The term *switch* is often used loosely to include devices such as routers and bridges, as well as devices that may distribute traffic based on load or based on application content (e.g., a Web URL identifier).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A router is an internetworking device that forwards packets between networks by processing the routing information included in the packet or datagram (Internet protocol information from layer 3).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The routing information is often processed in conjunction with the routing table (or forwarding table).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A router uses its routing table to determine where to forward packets.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A destination in a routing table can include a black hole because data can go into it; however, no further processing is done for said data, i.e., the packets are dropped.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Modems (MOdulator-DEModulator) are used to connect network nodes via wire not originally designed for digital network traffic, or for wireless.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] To do this, one or more carrier signals are modulated by the digital signal to produce an analog signal that can be tailored to give the required properties for transmission.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Modems are commonly used for telephone lines, using a digital subscriber line technology.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A firewall is a network device for controlling network security and access rules.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Firewalls are typically configured to reject access requests from unrecognized sources while allowing actions from recognized ones.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The vital role firewalls play in network security grows in parallel with the constant increase in cyber attacks.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The study of network topology recognizes eight basic topologies: point-to-point, bus, star, ring or circular, mesh, tree, hybrid, or daisy chain.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The simplest topology with a dedicated link between two endpoints.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Easiest to understand of the variations of point-to-point topology is a point-to-point communication channel that appears, to the user, to be permanently associated with the two endpoints.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A child's tin can telephone is one example of a *physical dedicated* channel.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Using circuit-switching or packet-switching technologies, a point-to-point circuit can be set up dynamically and dropped when no longer needed.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Switched point-to-point topologies are the basic model of conventional telephony.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The value of a permanent point-to-point network is unimpeded communications between the two endpoints.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The value of an on-demand point-to-point connection is proportional to the number of potential pairs of subscribers and has been expressed as Metcalfe's Law.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Daisy chaining is accomplished by connecting each computer in series to the next.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] If a message is intended for a computer partway down the line, each system bounces it along in sequence until it reaches the destination.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A daisy-chained network can take two basic forms: linear and ring.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In local area networks using bus topology, each node is connected by interface connectors to a single central cable.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This is the 'bus', also referred to as the backbone, or trunk – all data transmission between nodes in the network is transmitted over this common transmission medium and is able to be received by all nodes in the network simultaneously.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A signal containing the address of the intended receiving machine travels from a source machine in both directions to all machines connected to the bus until it finds the intended recipient, which then accepts the data.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] If the machine address does not match the intended address for the data, the data portion of the signal is ignored.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Since the bus topology consists of only one wire, it is less expensive to implement than other topologies, but the savings are offset by the higher cost of managing the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Additionally, since the network is dependent on the single cable, it can be the single point of failure of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In this topology, data being transferred may be accessed by any node.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In a linear bus network, all of the nodes of the network are connected to a common transmission medium, which has just two endpoints.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] When the electrical signal reaches the end of the bus, the signal is reflected back down the line, causing unwanted interference.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] To prevent this, the two endpoints of the bus are normally terminated with a device called a terminator.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In star topology (also called hub-and-spoke), every peripheral node (computer workstation or any other peripheral) is connected to a central node called a hub or switch.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The hub is the server and the peripherals are the clients.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The network does not necessarily have to resemble a star to be classified as a star network, but all of the peripheral nodes on the network must be connected to one central hub.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] All traffic that traverses the network passes through the central hub, which acts as a signal repeater.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The star topology is considered the easiest topology to design and implement.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] One advantage of the star topology is the simplicity of adding additional nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The primary disadvantage of the star topology is that the hub represents a single point of failure.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Also, since all peripheral communication must flow through the central hub, the aggregate central bandwidth forms a network bottleneck for large clusters.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The extended star network topology extends a physical star topology by one or more repeaters between the central node and the peripheral (or 'spoke') nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The repeaters are used to extend the maximum transmission distance of the physical layer, the point-to-point distance between the central node and the peripheral nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Repeaters allow greater transmission distance, further than would be possible using just the transmitting power of the central node.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The use of repeaters can also overcome limitations from the standard upon which the physical layer is based.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A physical extended star topology in which repeaters are replaced with hubs or switches is a type of hybrid network topology and is referred to as a physical hierarchical star topology, although some texts make no distinction between the two topologies.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A physical hierarchical star topology can also be referred as a tier-star topology.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This topology differs from a tree topology in the way star networks are connected together.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A tier-star topology uses a central node, while a tree topology uses a central bus and can also be referred to as a star-bus network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A ring topology is a daisy chain in a closed loop.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Data travels around the ring in one direction.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] When one node sends data to another, the data passes through each intermediate node on the ring until it reaches its destination.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The intermediate nodes repeat (retransmit) the data to keep the signal strong.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Every node is a peer; there is no hierarchical relationship of clients and servers.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] If one node is unable to retransmit data, it severs communication between the nodes before and after it in the bus.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The value of fully meshed networks is proportional to the exponent of the number of subscribers, assuming that communicating groups of any two endpoints, up to and including all the endpoints, is approximated by Reed's Law.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In a *fully connected network*, all nodes are interconnected.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] (In graph theory this is called a complete graph.) The simplest fully connected network is a two-node network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A fully connected network doesn't need to use packet switching or broadcasting.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This makes it impractical for large networks.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This kind of topology does not trip and affect other nodes in the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In a partially connected network, certain nodes are connected to exactly one other node, but some nodes are connected to two or more other nodes with a point-to-point link.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This makes it possible to make use of some of the redundancy of mesh topology that is physically fully connected, without the expense and complexity required for a connection between every node in the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Hybrid topology is also known as hybrid network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Hybrid networks combine two or more topologies in such a way that the resulting network does not exhibit one of the standard topologies (e.g., bus, star, ring, etc.).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] For example, a tree network (or *star-bus network*) is a hybrid topology in which star networks are interconnected via bus networks.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] However, a tree network connected to another tree network is still topologically a tree network, not a distinct network type.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A hybrid topology is always produced when two different basic network topologies are connected.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A *star-ring* network consists of two or more ring networks connected using a multistation access unit (MAU) as a centralized hub.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Two other hybrid network types are *hybrid mesh* and *hierarchical star*.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The **star topology** reduces the probability of a network failure by connecting all of the peripheral nodes (computers, etc.) to a central node.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] When the physical star topology is applied to a logical bus network such as Ethernet, this central node (traditionally a hub) rebroadcasts all transmissions received from any peripheral node to all peripheral nodes on the network, sometimes including the originating node.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] All peripheral nodes may thus communicate with all others by transmitting to, and receiving from, the central node only.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The failure of a transmission line linking any peripheral node to the central node will result in the isolation of that peripheral node from all others, but the remaining peripheral nodes will be unaffected.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] However, the disadvantage is that the failure of the central node will cause the failure of all of the peripheral nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] If the central node is *passive*, the originating node must be able to tolerate the reception of an echo of its own transmission, delayed by the two-way round trip transmission time (i.e. to and from the central node) plus any delay generated in the central node.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] An *active* star network has an active central node that usually has the means to prevent echo-related problems.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] **hierarchical topology**) can be viewed as a collection of star networks arranged in a hierarchy.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This tree structure has individual peripheral nodes (e.g., leaves) which are required to transmit to and receive from one other node only and are not required to act as repeaters or regenerators.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Unlike the star network, the functionality of the central node may be distributed.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] As in the conventional star network, individual nodes may thus still be isolated from the network by a single-point failure of a transmission path to the node.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] If a link connecting a leaf fails, that leaf is isolated; if a connection to a non-leaf node fails, an entire section of the network becomes isolated from the rest.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] To alleviate the amount of network traffic that comes from broadcasting all signals to all nodes, more advanced central nodes were developed that are able to keep track of the identities of the nodes that are connected to the network.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] These network switches will *learn* the layout of the network by *listening* on each port during normal data transmission, examining the data packets and recording the address/identifier of each connected node and which port it is connected to in a lookup table held in memory.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This lookup table then allows future transmissions to be forwarded to the intended destination only.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Daisy chain topology is a way of connecting network nodes in a linear or ring structure.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] It is used to transmit messages from one node to the next until they reach the destination node.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A daisy chain network can have two types: linear and ring.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A linear daisy chain network is like an electrical series, where the first and last nodes are not connected.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A ring daisy chain network is where the first and last nodes are connected, forming a loop.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In a partially connected mesh topology, there are at least two nodes with two or more paths between them to provide redundant paths in case the link providing one of the paths fails.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Decentralization is often used to compensate for the single-point-failure disadvantage that is present when using a single device as a central node (e.g., in star and tree networks).
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A special kind of mesh, limiting the number of hops between two nodes, is a hypercube.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] The number of arbitrary forks in mesh networks makes them more difficult to design and implement, but their decentralized nature makes them very useful.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This is similar in some ways to a grid network, where a linear or ring topology is used to connect systems in multiple directions.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A multidimensional ring has a toroidal topology, for instance.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] A *fully connected network*, *complete topology*, or *full mesh topology* is a network topology in which there is a direct link between all pairs of nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] In a fully connected network with n nodes, there are ${\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}\,$ direct links.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] Networks designed with this topology are usually very expensive to set up, but provide a high degree of reliability due to the multiple paths for data that are provided by the large number of redundant links between nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/network-topology] This topology is mostly seen in military applications.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] A **routing protocol** specifies how routers communicate with each other to distribute information that enables them to select paths between nodes on a computer network.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Routers perform the traffic directing functions on the Internet; data packets are forwarded through the networks of the internet from router to router until they reach their destination computer.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Routing algorithms determine the specific choice of route.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Each router has a prior knowledge only of networks attached to it directly.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] A routing protocol shares this information first among immediate neighbors, and then throughout the network.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] This way, routers gain knowledge of the topology of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] The ability of routing protocols to dynamically adjust to changing conditions such as disabled connections and components and route data around obstructions is what gives the Internet its fault tolerance and high availability.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Certain additional characteristics such as multilayer interfacing may also be employed as a means of distributing uncompromised networking gateways to authorized ports.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] This has the added benefit of preventing issues with routing protocol loops.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Many routing protocols are defined in technical standards documents called RFCs.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Interior gateway protocols (IGPs) exchange routing information within a single routing domain.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Exterior gateway protocols exchange routing information between autonomous systems.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Many software implementations exist for most of the common routing protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Examples of open-source applications are Bird Internet routing daemon, Quagga, GNU Zebra, OpenBGPD, OpenOSPFD, and XORP.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Some network certification courses distinguish between routing protocols and *routed* protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] A **routed protocol** is used to deliver application traffic.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] It provides appropriate addressing information in its internet layer or network layer to allow a packet to be forwarded from one network to another.
[src:mesh-networking/routing-protocol] Examples of routed protocols are the Internet Protocol (IP) and Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] A **wireless mesh network** (**WMN**) is a communications network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] A **mesh** refers to rich interconnection among devices or nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks often consist of mesh clients, mesh routers and gateways.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] If nodes constantly or frequently move, the mesh spends more time updating routes than delivering data.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] In a wireless mesh network, topology tends to be more static, so that routes computation can converge and delivery of data to their destinations can occur.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Hence, this is a low-mobility centralized form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Also, because it sometimes relies on static nodes to act as gateways, it is not a truly all-wireless ad hoc network.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh clients are often laptops, cell phones, and other wireless devices.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh routers forward traffic to and from the gateways, which may or may not be connected to the Internet.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The coverage area of all radio nodes working as a single network is sometimes called a mesh cloud.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Access to this mesh cloud depends on the radio nodes working together to create a radio network.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] A mesh network is reliable and offers redundancy.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] When one node can no longer operate, the rest of the nodes can still communicate with each other, directly or through one or more intermediate nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks can self form and self heal.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks work with different wireless technologies including 802.11, 802.15, 802.16, cellular technologies and need not be restricted to any one technology or protocol.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh radio networks were originally developed for military applications, such that every node could dynamically serve as a router for every other node.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] In that way, even in the event of a failure of some nodes, the remaining nodes could continue to communicate with each other, and, if necessary, serve as uplinks for the other nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Early wireless mesh network nodes had a single half-duplex radio that, at any one instant, could either transmit or receive, but not both at the same time.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This was accompanied by the development of shared mesh networks.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This was subsequently superseded by more complex radio hardware that could receive packets from an upstream node and transmit packets to a downstream node simultaneously (on a different frequency or a different CDMA channel).
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This allowed the development of switched mesh networks.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] As the size, cost, and power requirements of radios declined further, nodes could be cost-effectively equipped with multiple radios.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This, in turn, permitted each radio to handle a different function, for instance, one radio for client access, and another for backhaul services.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Work in this field has been aided by the use of game theory methods to analyze strategies for the allocation of resources and routing of packets.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh architecture is a first step towards providing cost effective and low mobility over a specific coverage area.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh infrastructure is, in effect, a network of routers minus the cabling between nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] It is built of peer radio devices that do not have to be cabled to a wired port like traditional WLAN access points (AP) do.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh infrastructure carries data over large distances by splitting the distance into a series of short hops.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Intermediate nodes not only boost the signal, but cooperatively pass data from point A to point B by making forwarding decisions based on their knowledge of the network, i.e. perform routing by first deriving the topology of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Wireless mesh networks is a relatively "stable-topology" network except for the occasional failure of nodes or addition of new nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The path of traffic, being aggregated from a large number of end users, changes infrequently.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Practically all the traffic in an infrastructure mesh network is either forwarded to or from a gateway, while in wireless ad hoc networks or client mesh networks the traffic flows between arbitrary pairs of nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] If rate of mobility among nodes are high, i.e., link breaks happen frequently, wireless mesh networks start to break down and have low communication performance.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This type of infrastructure can be decentralized (with no central server) or centrally managed (with a central server).
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Both are relatively inexpensive, and can be very reliable and resilient, as each node needs only transmit as far as the next node.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Nodes act as routers to transmit data from nearby nodes to peers that are too far away to reach in a single hop, resulting in a network that can span larger distances.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The topology of a mesh network must be relatively stable, i.e., not too much mobility.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] If one node drops out of the network, due to hardware failure or any other reason, its neighbors can quickly find another route using a routing protocol.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Mesh networks may involve either fixed or mobile devices.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] An important possible application for wireless mesh networks is VoIP.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] By using a quality of service scheme, the wireless mesh may support routing local telephone calls through the mesh.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Most applications in wireless mesh networks are similar to those in wireless ad hoc networks.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The principle is similar to the way packets travel around the wired Internet – data hops from one device to another until it eventually reaches its destination.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Dynamic routing algorithms implemented in each device allow this to happen.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] To implement such dynamic routing protocols, each device needs to communicate routing information to other devices in the network.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Each device then determines what to do with the data it receives – either pass it on to the next device or keep it, depending on the protocol.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The routing algorithm used should attempt to always ensure that the data takes the most appropriate (fastest) route to its destination.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Multi-radio mesh refers to having different radios operating at different frequencies to interconnect nodes in a mesh.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This means there is a unique frequency used for each wireless hop and thus a dedicated CSMA collision domain.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] With more radio bands, communication throughput is likely to increase as a result of more available communication channels.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This is similar to providing dual or multiple radio paths to transmit and receive data.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] technologies is further investigated, since their complexity and cost are still too high for wide commercialization.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Tremendous efforts on research of frequency-agile techniques are being performed for increased efficiency.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Cross-layer research is a popular current research topic where information is shared between different communications layers to increase the knowledge and current state of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] This could facilitate development of new and more efficient protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] A joint protocol that addresses various design problems—routing, scheduling, channel assignment etc.—can achieve higher performance since these problems are strongly co-related.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Note that careless cross-layer design can lead to code that is difficult to maintain and extend.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] a new SDN architecture for WMNs is explored that eliminates the need for multi-hop flooding of route information and therefore enables WMNs to easily expand.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The key idea is to split network control and data forwarding by using two separate frequency bands.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The forwarding nodes and the SDN controller exchange link-state information and other network control signaling in one of the bands, while actual data forwarding takes place in the other band.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] A WMN can be seen as a group of nodes (clients or routers) that cooperate to provide connectivity.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] , where clients serve as routers to forward data packets, is exposed to many types of attacks that can interrupt the whole network and cause denial of service (DoS) or Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS).
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] A number of wireless community networks have been started as grassroots projects across the world at various points in time.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] There are more than 70 competing schemes for routing packets across mesh networks.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] The IEEE has developed a set of standards under the title 802.11s.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] A less thorough list can be found at list of ad hoc routing protocols.
[src:mesh-networking/wireless-mesh-network] Standard autoconfiguration protocols, such as DHCP or IPv6 stateless autoconfiguration may be used over mesh networks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The technology defined by the Zigbee specification is intended to be simpler and less expensive than other wireless personal area networks (WPANs), such as Bluetooth, or more general wireless networking standards, such as Wi-Fi (or Li-Fi).
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Applications include wireless light switches, home energy monitors, traffic management systems, and other consumer and industrial equipment that requires short-range, low-rate wireless data transfer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Its low power consumption limits transmission distances to 10–100 meters (33–328 ft) line-of-sight, depending on power output and environmental characteristics.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee devices can transmit data over long distances by passing data through a mesh network of intermediate devices to reach more distant ones.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee is typically used in low-data-rate applications that require long battery life and secure networking.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] (Zigbee networks are secured by 128-bit symmetric encryption keys.) Zigbee has a defined rate of up to 250 kbit/s, best suited for intermittent data transmissions from a sensor or input device.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee was conceived in 1998, standardized in 2003, and revised in 2006.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The name refers to the waggle dance of honey bees after their return to the beehive.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee is a low-power wireless mesh network standard delivering low-latency communication and targeted at battery-powered devices in wireless control and monitoring applications.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee chips are typically integrated with radios and microcontrollers.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee operates in the industrial, scientific and medical (ISM) radio bands, with the 2.4 GHz band being primarily used for lighting and home automation devices in most jurisdictions worldwide.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Devices for commercial utility metering and medical device data collection often use *sub-GHz* frequencies: 902–928 MHz in North America, Australia, and Israel, 868–870 MHz in Europe, 779–787 MHz in China.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Data rates vary from around 20 kbit/s for sub-GHz bands to around 250 kbit/s for the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee builds on the physical layer and media access control defined in the IEEE 802.15.4 standard for low-rate wireless personal area networks (WPANs).
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Zigbee specification includes four additional key components: network layer, application layer, *Zigbee Device Objects* (ZDOs) and manufacturer-defined application objects.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] ZDOs are responsible for tasks including keeping track of device roles, managing requests to join a network, and discovering and securing devices.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Zigbee network layer natively supports star and tree, and generic mesh networking topologies.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Every network must have one coordinator device.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Within star networks, the coordinator must be the central node.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Both trees and meshes allow the use of Zigbee routers to extend communication at the network layer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Another defining feature of Zigbee is facilities for carrying out secure communications, protecting the establishment and transport of cryptographic keys, ciphering frames, and controlling devices.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] For this, it builds on the basic security framework defined in IEEE 802.15.4.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee-style self-organizing ad hoc digital radio networks were conceived in the 1990s.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The IEEE 802.15.4-2003 Zigbee specification was ratified on December 14, 2004.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Connectivity Standards Alliance (formerly Zigbee Alliance) announced availability of Specification 1.0 on June 13, 2005, known as the *ZigBee 2004 Specification*.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In September 2006, the *Zigbee 2006 Specification* was announced, obsoleting the 2004 stack The 2006 specification replaces the message and key–value pair structure used in the 2004 stack with a *cluster library*.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The library is a set of standardised commands, attributes and global artifacts organised under groups known as clusters with names such as Smart Energy, Home Automation, and **Zigbee Light Link**.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Since its unveiling, Dotdot has functioned as the default application layer for almost all Zigbee devices.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee Pro, also known as Zigbee 2007, was finalized in 2007.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] A Zigbee Pro device may join and operate on a legacy Zigbee network and vice versa.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Due to differences in routing options, a Zigbee Pro device must become a non-routing Zigbee End Device (ZED) on a legacy Zigbee network, and a legacy Zigbee device must become a ZED on a Zigbee Pro network.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It operates using the 2.4 GHz ISM band and adds a sub-GHz band.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee protocols are intended for embedded applications requiring low power consumption and tolerating low data rates.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The resulting network will use very little power—individual devices must have a battery life of at least two years to pass certification.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee is not for situations with high mobility among nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Hence, it is not suitable for tactical ad hoc radio networks in the battlefield, where high data rate and high mobility is present and needed.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The first Zigbee application profile, Home Automation, was announced November 2, 2007.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Additional application profiles have since been published.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The **Zigbee Smart Energy 2.0** specifications define an Internet Protocol-based communication protocol to monitor, control, inform, and automate the delivery and use of energy and water.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It is an enhancement of the Zigbee Smart Energy version 1 specifications.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It adds services for plug-in electric vehicle charging, installation, configuration and firmware download, prepay services, user information and messaging, load control, demand response and common information and application profile interfaces for wired and wireless networks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee Smart Energy relies on Zigbee IP, a network layer that routes standard IPv6 traffic over IEEE 802.15.4 using 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In 2009, the Radio Frequency for Consumer Electronics Consortium (RF4CE) and Connectivity Standards Alliance (formerly Zigbee Alliance) agreed to jointly deliver a standard for radio frequency remote controls.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee RF4CE is designed for a broad range of consumer electronics products, such as TVs and set-top boxes.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It promised many advantages over existing remote control solutions, including richer communication and increased reliability, enhanced features and flexibility, interoperability, and no line-of-sight barrier.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Zigbee RF4CE specification uses a subset of Zigbee functionality allowing to run on smaller memory configurations in lower-cost devices, such as remote control of consumer electronics.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The radio design used by Zigbee has few analog stages and uses digital circuits wherever possible.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Products that integrate the radio and microcontroller into a single module are available.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Zigbee qualification process involves a full validation of the requirements of the physical layer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] All radios derived from the same validated semiconductor mask set would enjoy the same RF characteristics.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee radios have very tight constraints on power and bandwidth.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] An uncertified physical layer that malfunctions can increase the power consumption of other devices on a Zigbee network.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Thus, radios are tested with guidance given by Clause 6 of the 802.15.4-2006 Standard.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] This standard specifies operation in the unlicensed 2.4 to 2.4835 GHz (worldwide), 902 to 928 MHz (Americas and Australia) and 868 to 868.6 MHz (Europe) ISM bands.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Sixteen channels are allocated in the 2.4 GHz band, spaced 5 MHz apart, though using only 2 MHz of bandwidth each.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The radios use direct-sequence spread spectrum coding, which is managed by the digital stream into the modulator.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Binary phase-shift keying (BPSK) is used in the 868 and 915 MHz bands, and offset quadrature phase-shift keying (OQPSK) that transmits two bits per symbol is used in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The raw, over-the-air data rate is 250 kbit/s per channel in the 2.4 GHz band, 40 kbit/s per channel in the 915 MHz band, and 20 kbit/s in the 868 MHz band.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The actual data throughput will be less than the maximum specified bit rate because of the packet overhead and processing delays.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] For indoor applications at 2.4 GHz, the transmission distance is 10–20 m, depending on the construction materials, the number of walls to be penetrated and the output power permitted in the geographical location.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The output power of the radios is generally 0–20 dBm (1–100 mW).
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The current Zigbee protocols support beacon-enabled and non-beacon-enabled networks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In non-beacon-enabled networks, an unslotted CSMA/CA channel access mechanism is used.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In this type of network, Zigbee routers typically have their receivers continuously active, requiring additional power.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] However, this allows for heterogeneous networks in which some devices receive continuously while others transmit when necessary.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The typical example of a heterogeneous network is a wireless light switch: The Zigbee node at the lamp may constantly receive, since it is reliably powered by the mains supply to the lamp, while a battery-powered light switch would remain asleep until the switch is thrown.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In this case, the switch wakes up, sends a command to the lamp, receives an acknowledgment, and returns to sleep.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In such a network, the lamp node will be at least a Zigbee router, if not the Zigbee coordinator; the switch node is typically a Zigbee end device.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In beacon-enabled networks, Zigbee routers transmit periodic beacons to confirm their presence to other network nodes.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Nodes may sleep between beacons, thus extending their battery life.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Beacon intervals depend on data rate; they may range from 15.36 milliseconds to 251.65824 seconds at 250 kbit/s, from 24 milliseconds to 393.216 seconds at 40 kbit/s and from 48 milliseconds to 786.432 seconds at 20 kbit/s.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Long beacon intervals require precise timing, which can be expensive to implement in low-cost products.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In general, the Zigbee protocols minimize the time the radio is on, so as to reduce power use.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In beaconing networks, nodes only need to be active while a beacon is being transmitted.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In non-beacon-enabled networks, power consumption is decidedly asymmetrical: Some devices are always active while others spend most of their time sleeping.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Except for Smart Energy Profile 2.0, Zigbee devices are required to conform to the IEEE 802.15.4-2003 Low-rate Wireless Personal Area Network (LR-WPAN) standard.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The standard specifies the lower protocol layers—the physical layer (PHY), and the media access control portion of the data link layer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The basic channel access mode is carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA).
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] That is, the nodes communicate in a way somewhat analogous to how humans converse: a node briefly checks to see that other nodes are not talking before it starts.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The main functions of the network layer are to ensure correct use of the MAC sublayer and provide a suitable interface for use by the next upper layer, namely the application layer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The network layer deals with network functions such as connecting, disconnecting, and setting up networks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It can establish a network, allocate addresses, and add and remove devices.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] This layer makes use of star, mesh and tree topologies.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The data entity of the transport layer creates and manages protocol data units at the direction of the application layer and performs routing according to the current topology.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The control entity handles the configuration of new devices and establishes new networks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It can determine whether a neighboring device belongs to the network and discover new neighbors and routers.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The routing protocol used by the network layer is AODV.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] To find a destination device, AODV is used to broadcast a route request to all of its neighbors.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The neighbors then broadcast the request to their neighbors and onward until the destination is reached.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Once the destination is reached, a route reply is sent via unicast transmission following the lowest cost path back to the source.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Once the source receives the reply, it updates its routing table with the destination address of the next hop in the path and the associated path cost.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The application layer is the highest-level layer defined by the specification and is the effective interface of the Zigbee system to its end users.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It comprises the majority of components added by the Zigbee specification: both ZDO (Zigbee device object) and its management procedures, together with application objects defined by the manufacturer, are considered part of this layer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] This layer binds tables, sends messages between bound devices, manages group addresses, reassembles packets, and transports data.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It is responsible for providing service to Zigbee device profiles.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The *ZDO* (Zigbee device object), a protocol in the Zigbee protocol stack, is responsible for overall device management, security keys, and policies.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It is responsible for defining the role of a device as either coordinator or end device, as mentioned above, but also for the discovery of new devices on the network and the identification of their offered services.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It may then go on to establish secure links with external devices and reply to binding requests accordingly.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The application support sublayer (APS) is the other main standard component of the stack, and as such, it offers a well-defined interface and control services.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It works as a bridge between the network layer and the other elements of the application layer: it keeps up-to-date binding tables in the form of a database, which can be used to find appropriate devices depending on the services that are needed and those that the different devices offer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] As the union between both specified layers, it also routes messages across the layers of the protocol stack.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] An application may consist of communicating objects that cooperate to carry out the desired tasks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Tasks will typically be largely local to each device, such as the control of each household appliance.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The focus of Zigbee is to distribute work among many different devices that reside within individual Zigbee nodes, which in turn form a network.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The objects that form the network communicate using the facilities provided by APS, supervised by ZDO interfaces.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Within a single device, up to 240 application objects can exist, numbered in the range 1–240.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] 0 is reserved for the ZDO data interface and 255 for broadcast; the 241–254 range is not in use but may be in the future.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Addressing is also part of the application layer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] A network node consists of an IEEE 802.15.4-conformant radio transceiver and one or more device descriptions (collections of attributes that can be polled or set or can be monitored through events).
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The transceiver is the basis for addressing, and devices within a node are specified by an *endpoint identifier* in the range 1 to 240.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] For applications to communicate, the devices that support them must use a common application protocol (types of messages, formats and so on); these sets of conventions are grouped in *profiles*.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Furthermore, binding is decided upon by matching input and output cluster identifiers unique within the context of a given profile and associated with an incoming or outgoing data flow in a device.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Binding tables contain source and destination pairs.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Depending on the available information, device discovery may follow different methods.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] When the network address is known, the IEEE address can be requested using unicast communication.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] When it is not, petitions are broadcast.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] End devices will simply respond with the requested address, while a network coordinator or a router will also send the addresses of all the devices associated with it.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] This extended discovery protocol permits external devices to find out about devices in a network and the services that they offer, which endpoints can report when queried by the discovering device (which has previously obtained their addresses).
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The use of cluster identifiers enforces the binding of complementary entities using the binding tables, which are maintained by Zigbee coordinators, as the table must always be available within a network and coordinators are most likely to have a permanent power supply.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Backups, managed by higher-level layers, may be needed by some applications.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Binding requires an established communication link; after it exists, whether to add a new node to the network is decided, according to the application and security policies.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Communication can happen right after the association.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] *Direct addressing* uses both radio address and endpoint identifier, whereas indirect addressing uses every relevant field (address, endpoint, cluster, and attribute) and requires that they are sent to the network coordinator, which maintains associations and translates requests for communication.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Indirect addressing is particularly useful to keep some devices very simple and minimize their need for storage.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Besides these two methods, *broadcast* to all endpoints in a device is available, and *group addressing* is used to communicate with groups of endpoints belonging to a specified set of devices.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] As one of its defining features, Zigbee provides facilities for carrying out secure communications, protecting the establishment and transport of cryptographic keys and encrypting data.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] It builds on the basic security framework defined in IEEE 802.15.4.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The basic mechanism to ensure confidentiality is the adequate protection of all keying material.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Keys are the cornerstone of the security architecture; as such, their protection is of paramount importance, and keys are never supposed to be transported through an insecure channel.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] A momentary exception to this rule occurs during the initial phase of the addition to the network of a previously unconfigured device.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Trust must be assumed in the initial installation of the keys, as well as in the processing of security information.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Zigbee network model must take particular care of security considerations, as ad hoc networks may be physically accessible to external devices.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Also, the state of the working environment cannot be predicted.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Within the protocol stack, different network layers are not cryptographically separated, so access policies are needed, and conventional design assumed.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The open trust model within a device allows for key sharing, which notably decreases potential cost.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Nevertheless, the layer that creates a frame is responsible for its security.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] As malicious devices may exist, every network layer payload must be ciphered, so unauthorized traffic can be immediately cut off.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The exception, again, is the transmission of the network key, which confers a unified security layer to the grid to a new connecting device.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Zigbee security architecture is based on CCM*, which adds encryption- and integrity-only features to CCM mode.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Zigbee uses 128-bit keys to implement its security mechanisms.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] A key can be associated either with a network, being usable by Zigbee layers and the MAC sublayer, or to a link, acquired through pre-installation, agreement or transport.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Establishment of link keys is based on a master key that controls link key correspondence.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Ultimately, at least, the initial master key must be obtained through a secure medium (transport or pre-installation), as the security of the whole network depends on it.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Link and master keys are only visible to the application layer.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Different services use different one-way variations of the link key to avoid leaks and security risks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Key distribution is one of the most important security functions of the network.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] A secure network will designate one special device, the *trust center*, which other devices trust for the distribution of security keys.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Ideally, devices will have the trust center address and initial master key preloaded; if a momentary vulnerability is allowed, it will be sent as described above.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Typical applications without special security needs will use a network key provided by the trust center (through the initially insecure channel) to communicate.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Thus, the trust center maintains both the network key and provides point-to-point security.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Devices will only accept communications originating from a key supplied by the trust center, except for the initial master key.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] According to the German computer e-magazine *Heise Online*, Zigbee Home Automation 1.2 uses fallback keys for encryption negotiation, which are known and can not be changed.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] This makes the encryption highly vulnerable.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] This ensures that all network traffic is securely encrypted even while pairing the device.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In addition, all Zigbee devices need to randomize their network key, no matter which pairing method they use, thereby improving security for older devices.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] The Zigbee coordinator within the Zigbee network can be set to deny access to devices that do not employ this key randomization, further increasing security.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] In addition, the Zigbee 3.0 protocol features countermeasures against removing already paired devices from the network with the intention of listening to the key exchange when re-pairing.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] Network simulators, like ns-2, OMNeT++, OPNET, and NetSim can be used to simulate IEEE 802.15.4 Zigbee networks.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] These simulators come with open source C or C++ libraries for users to modify.
[src:mesh-networking/zigbee] This way, users can determine the validity of new algorithms before hardware implementation.
